== Solar Sail Performance

The momentum of a given photon can be calculated by substituting the mass energy equivalence equation into the momentum equation, yielding *@21-photon-momentum*. The resulting momentum change is also shown in *@21-photon-momentum*.

$
  E = m c^2 quad quad p = m c quad --> quad p = (E/c^2)c = E/c \
  Delta p = (Delta E)/c
$<21-photon-momentum>

The change of energy can also be written in the form shown in *@21-incident-energy* where $A$ is the area, $W$ is the energy flux and $Delta t$ is the change in time.

$
  Delta E = W A Delta t
$<21-incident-energy>

An expression for the pressure exerted on the surface due to the photons can also be derived and is shown in *@21-photon-pressure*.

$
  P = 1/A ((Delta p)/(Delta t))
$<21-photon-pressure>

A final equation for solar pressure can be developed by substituting *@21-incident-energy* into *@21-photon-momentum* and then the resulting expression into *@21-photon-pressure*, this yields *@21-final-photon-pressure*.

$
  Delta p = (Delta E)/c = (W A Delta t)/c quad --> quad P = 1/A ((Delta p)/(Delta t)) = 1/A ((W A Delta t)/(c Delta t)) \
  therefore P = W/c
$<21-final-photon-pressure>

To find the thrust generated by a solar sail, *@21-final-photon-pressure* can be multiplied by the area, this final expression is shown in *@21-solar-sail-thrust*.

$
  F = P A = (W A)/c
$<21-solar-sail-thrust>

However, *@21-solar-sail-thrust* is an idealized equation, in reality there are losses due to wrinkles, absorption and the angle of incidence, these are included in the final corrected expression shown in *@21-solar-sail-corrected-thrust*.

